<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0802-B"><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>At the same time, average air temperatures across most of the Arctic region from January to August 2005 were as much as 5.4 degrees F warmer than average temperature over the last 50 years, said the team of researchers from two universities and NASA.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>&quot;The time is past to debate the impact of climate change.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;The evidence is now so strong that the scientific community is convinced that global warming is the cause.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>In Russia, 20 percent of which lies above the Arctic Circle, melting of the permafrost threatens the foundations of homes, factories, pipelines.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="90" label="Melting permafrost damages Russian infrastructure" weight="1"/><scu uid="92" label="Melting permafrost damages Russian gas pipelines" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>For us working here, it hits you like a ton of bricks when you see it.&quot;</line><line>It has become more difficult to drive dogs sleds because the ice between the icebergs isn't solid anymore.&quot;</line><line>With warmer temperatures, some bacteria, plants and animals could disappear, while others will grow and thrive.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>Eventually, homes will be lost, and maybe all of Bykovsky.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>Its impact has however been limited, partly because the world's biggest polluter nation the United States refused to sign up.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="38"><scu uid="78" label="countries agree Kyoto Protocol not enough" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>That's the lowest measurement of Arctic sea ice cover ever recorded, the researchers said.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="20,32,49"><scu uid="116" label="Arctic sea ice melting faster" weight="2"/><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>The Arctic's atmosphere is warming twice as fast as elsewhere on earth, and experts have warned that the region's ice could melt away completely by the end of this century, endangering many animal species and the traditional lifestyle of Inuits and Lapplanders.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="3" sums="10,36,40"><scu uid="107" label="Wildlife are threatened" weight="1"/><scu uid="120" label="Arctic sea ice could disappear this century" weight="1"/><scu uid="139" label="Arctic of today radically changed within next century without action worldwide" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>President George W. Bush said the scientific evidence for climate change was incomplete and complained that Kyoto's legal requirements for reducing emissions were too costly for the US economy.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>The report comes just days after environmental ministers and officials from 23 countries met in Greenland to call on governments to stop arguing over global warming and start acting.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>In Greenland, Anthon Utuaq, a 68-year-old retired hunter, said he is worried a warmer climate will make it more difficult for his son to continue the family trade.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>&quot;High in the Arctic, in our interior and along our coasts, the country we know is being transformed,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>&quot;It's starting to snowball,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Since the 1970s, scientists have monitored the Columbia Glacier with satellites, lasers and aerial photography and found that the increase of its so-called calving rate might be dangerous to shipping lanes in the sound.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>The ship, which has been traveling around Greenland to observe the effects of global warming, will be open for tours at the Boston Harbor Shipyard and Marina, 256 Marginal St., on Sept. 17 and 18, from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>In the Antarctic, only 1 percent is melting,&quot; said Bjoern Lomborg, a Danish researcher who claims the threat of global warming has been exaggerated.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>The report was issued following a weeklong meeting of scientists that examined how the Arctic environment and climate interact and how that system would respond as global temperatures rise.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>&quot;We are already starting with the post-Kyoto issues.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>Climate change could thaw the top 11 feet (3.35 meters) of permafrost in most areas of the Northern Hemisphere by 2100, altering ecosystems across Alaska, Canada and Russia, according to a federal study.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="0"><scu uid="96" label="Northern Hemisphere permafrost could thaw by 2100" weight="2"/><scu uid="103" label="Thawing permafrost altering ecosystems" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>Inuit leaders, like Sheila Watt-Cloutier whose efforts won her the 2005 Sophie environment prize in Norway earlier this year, are trying to draw attention to the impact of climate change and pollution on the traditional lifestyles of the Arctic's indigenous people.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>The rapid retreat of Greenland glaciers suggest that climate change is a factor, Hamilton said.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="3" sums="37,57,6"><scu uid="123" label="Glacier Sermeg melted faster" weight="1"/><scu uid="124" label="Glacier Sermilik melted faster" weight="1"/><scu uid="125" label="Glacier Kangerdlugssuag melted faster" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;Greenland was perceived as this huge solid place that would never melt,&quot; said Robert Corell of the American Meteorological Society.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>Lawrence said he hopes to collaborate with Romanovsky to fine-tune future studies to deal with those deeper layers.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Sea levels have swelled globally an estimated 4 inches to 8 inches (10 centimeters to 20 centimeters) over the past century due to melting glaciers and polar ice _ enough to cause some low-lying places to be awash at high tide or during severe storms.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Martin blasted the small but influential minority of skeptics who doubted that Man had interfered with Earth's delicate climate balance.</line><line>The meeting's big focus is the future of the Kyoto Protocol, the troubled UN pact on curbing greenhouse gases.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>Glacial breakdown mechanisms currently being studied could speed that up considerably.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>Across the Arctic, indigenous tribes like the Inuit and the Samis, or Laplanders, whose traditions shaped by centuries of living in extremes of cold and ice are noticing changes in weather and wildlife.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="16"><scu uid="107" label="Wildlife are threatened" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>Rising temperatures are also a concern in the Yamalo-Nenets region in Western Siberia, said Alexandr Navyukhov, 49.</line><line>&quot;We know that temperatures have gone up and it's partly caused by man.</line><line>&quot;The polar bears need to be there to catch enough seals to see them through the summer in open warm water systems.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Pfeffer said climate change warming trends do not directly explain the shrinking Columbia Glacier and other tidewater glaciers.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>That could release additional greenhouse gases stored in the permafrost for thousands of years, he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Our permafrost is thawing, and releasing methane gas into the atmosphere.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>The ship is not accessible to wheelchairs and has lots of steep stairs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>For the 4 million people who live north of the Arctic Circle, in remote outposts and the improbable industrial centers built by Soviet decree, a changing climate presents new opportunities.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>That's because the bright white ice tends to reflect more of the sun's radiation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>In Bykovsky, a village of 457 on Russia's northeast coast, the shoreline is collapsing, creeping closer and closer to houses and tanks of heating oil, at a rate of 15 to 18 feet a year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>U.S. President George W. Bush's administration says participating in the pact would severely damage the U.S. economy.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>In the past, Arctic climate has included glacial periods with ice sheets extending into North America and Europe, and other times of relative warming.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="12,19,37,42,47,48,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>The U.N. Environment Program estimated that 15 percent of the region's lands were affected in 2001 by mining, oil and gas exploration, ports or other industrial incursions.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Alaska's Columbia Glacier _ about the size of Los Angeles _ has shrunk nine miles (15 kilometers) since the 1980s.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>&quot;We have not done enough considering the magnitude of the challenge,&quot; Finnish foreign minister Erkki Tuomioja told a meeting of the Barents council, which groups Russia, Norway, Sweden, Finland, Denmark, Iceland as well as the European Union.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>And, they suspect, the melting may only contribute to even higher arctic temperatures in the future.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;On the one hand it may look like good news, but breams are predatory fish that prey upon fish eggs, often of rare kinds of fish.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>Feedback can accelerate changes in the system, they said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>Last month, U.S. scientists issued a report saying the rate of ice melting in the Arctic is increasing and within a century could lead to summertime ice-free ocean conditions not seen in the area in a million years.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="8" sums="11,13,22,3,35,41,42,43"><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Although Greenland is the prime example, scientists say the effects of climate change are noticeable throughout the Arctic region, from the northward spread of spruce beetles in Canada to melting permafrost in Alaska and northern Russia.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="10,29,3,35,43"/></line><line>&quot;They will head north to colder places if it gets warmer.&quot;</line><line>&quot;If the climate gets warmer, it is probably bad for the reindeer.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>The scientists said they did not see any natural mechanism that could stop the loss of ice.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>To Greenland's Inuit population, it is also deeply worrisome.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>But it also threatens their environment, their homes and, for those whose traditions rely on the ice-bound wilderness, their culture.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>The most extreme scenario involved the melting of the top 11 feet of permafrost, or earth that remains frozen year-round.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>Freed by warming, waters once locked beneath ice are gnawing at coastal settlements around the Arctic Circle.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="23,51"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>With more of the dark ocean exposed, the seawater tends to absorb more heat and reduce the amount of solar energy reflected back into space.</line><line>The results have not yet been published in a scientific journal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>The rapid breakdown of the floating ice shelves observed in recent years, the experts said, could destabilize land-based ice sheets and glaciers behind them and cause faster melting and rise in sea levels than anticipated.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="131" label="Melting Greenland and Antarctic Ice Shelf double sea level" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>The UN's Kyoto treaty commits 39 industrial nations and territories to trim their output of six greenhouse gases -- especially carbon dioxide -- on average by five percent between 2008 and 2012, compared with 1990 levels.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>A 1982 map showed an area where two glaciers jutted a mile out to sea.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;When I was a child, the weather used to be more stable, it worries me to see and hear all this,&quot; Greenland Premier Hans Enoksen said on the sidelines of an environmental officials' meeting in Ilulissat last month.</line><line>Melting permafrost has damaged hundreds of buildings, railway lines, airport runways and gas pipelines in Russia, according to the Arctic Climate Impact Assessment, a report commissioned by the Arctic Council and released in 2004.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="90" label="Melting permafrost damages Russian infrastructure" weight="1"/><scu uid="91" label="Melting permafrost damages Russian airports" weight="1"/><scu uid="92" label="Melting permafrost damages Russian gas pipelines" weight="1"/><scu uid="93" label="Melting permafrost damages Russian railways" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Glaciers worldwide play a major role in discharging flowing water into oceans.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>&quot;You cannot do anything about it.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>The study was published Dec. 17 in the journal Geophysical Research Letters and presented earlier in the month at a science conference in San Francisco.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>(He's a fan of the proposed Cape Cod wind farm.)</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>Sea ice records in the Arctic are sketchy before 1978.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>A group of countries which fringe the Arctic waters of the Barents Sea gathered in Norway on Thursday and heard that they must go beyond the UN's Kyoto protocol to reduce greenhouse emissions.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="84" label="International meetings address climate change" weight="3"/><scu uid="86" label="international meetings address global warming" weight="3"/><scu uid="69" label="23 countries met" weight="2"/><scu uid="78" label="countries agree Kyoto Protocol not enough" weight="1"/><scu uid="89" label="Artic fringe countries met to discuss reducing greenhouse emissions" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>The Kyoto Protocol that took effect in February aims to reduce global greenhouse gas emissions.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="76" label="Kyoto Protocol commits 39 nations to reduce greenhouse gases" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;In the past we could walk on the ice in the fjord between the icebergs for a six-month period during the winter, drill holes and fish,&quot; said Joern Kristensen, a local fisherman.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>&quot;When the ice is gone, we're going to be in a world of hurt.&quot;IF YOU GO:</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>But a prediction that melting will reach deeply over the entire region goes too far, he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>The other glacier, Helheim, is speeding at about seven miles (11 kilometers) a year _ up from four miles (6.5 kilometers) a year during the same period.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>Within a century the melting could lead to summertime ice-free ocean conditions not seen in the area in a million years, the group said Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/><scu uid="120" label="Arctic sea ice could disappear this century" weight="1"/><scu uid="139" label="Arctic of today radically changed within next century without action worldwide" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Dupre, 44, of Grand Marais, Minn., attempted the first summer crossing of the Arctic Ocean in May to highlight the dangers of global warming.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>Norway plans to finance research into greenhouse emission recycling, and is currently studying the possibility of injecting carbon dioxide produced on land into offshore hydrocarbon fields, an environmentally-friendly measure which would also increase the productivity of North Sea oil and gas platforms.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>When Dupre reached the spot, the glaciers were not there.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>The researchers used satellite data from NASA, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the Defense Department, as well as data from Canadian satellites and weather observatories.</line><line>The observations showed 2.06 million square miles (5.27 million square kilometers) of sea ice as late as Sept. 19.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>There are fears that polar bears and some seal species could face extinction in just decades because of global warming.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>The scientists stopped short of directly blaming the melting trend on global warming but said they have few other explanations at this point.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>On good days, they would travel eight to 12 miles, but when they slept, drifting ice pushed them back the same distance or more.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>Since 2002, satellite data have revealed unusually early springtime melting in areas north of Siberia and Alaska.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="51"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>He is an ethnic nenet, a group that mostly lives off hunting, fishing and deer breeding.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>But that figure is likely to reach 80 percent in 2050, it said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>It is expected to lose an additional nine miles (15 kilometers) in the next 15 to 20 years before the bed of the glacier rises above sea level.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>Conference host Norway, the world's third-largest oil exporter, also said the Kyoto protocol needed to be respected and that new measures after 2012 had to be envisaged already.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>What is clear is that the average ocean temperature off Greenland's west coast has risen in recent years _ from 3.5 C (38.3 F) to 4.8 C (40.6 F) and glaciers have begun to retreat, said Carl Egede Boeggild, a glaciologist with Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland, a government agency.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>It's also 20 percent less than the average of end-of-summer ice pack cover measurements recorded since 1978.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Significant thinning of the Columbia Glacier is thought to be caused by huge chunks of iceberg that break off into the sound as a result of seawater pressure rather than climate change, Pfeffer said.</line><line>The glacier, which is up to 3,000 feet (915 meters) thick, has thinned up to 1,300 feet (390 meters) in some places over the last two decades.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>The Arctic is on thin ice.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="13,18,32,37,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>The time is past to pretend that any nation can stand alone, isolated from the global community... there can be no hiding on any island, in any city, within any country, no matter how prosperous, from the consequences of inaction.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>(20 inches) the scientists said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>As much as a quarter of the world's remaining oil and gas resources are believed to exist in the Arctic.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>In 1967, satellite imagery measured it moving at 7 kilometers (4.3 miles) per year.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>The gases act like an invisible blanket, trapping the Sun's heat and driving up the planet's surface temperature and disrupting climate cycles.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;In the U.S., global warming is a tomorrow issue....</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>The United States, the world's No. 1 carbon polluter, walked away from Kyoto in 2001.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>The ship will then travel to various New England ports, and is scheduled to reach Nantucket on Sept. 25.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>&quot;This is an issue we should take very seriously.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>Alaska's permafrost won't melt that fast or deep, said Vladimir Romanovsky, who monitors a network of permafrost observatories for the Geophysical Institute.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>We no longer need to ask people to imagine its effects, for now we can see them.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>Countries still dragging their feet, like the US, China and India, should be persuaded to contribute to these efforts, he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>&quot;I think probably the biggest surprise of the meeting was that no one could envision any interaction between the components that would act naturally to stop the trajectory to the new system,&quot; Overpeck said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>However, that may be largely offset by increased precipitation and glacial buildup in Antarctica, leading to increased sea level of about 50 centimeters</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Canadian Prime Minister Paul Martin, whose country is hosting the 12-day conference, said his nation's far north had become &quot;an incubator for the altered world of tomorrow.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;We now have breams in our river, which we didn't have in the past because that fish is typical for warmer regions,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Also, Larsen will be touring New England next month aboard Greenpeace's Arctic Sunrise, a 170-foot ice-breaker.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>AP writers Maria Danilova and Jim Heintz in Moscow, Karl Ritter in Stockholm, Sweden, and Beth Duff-Brown in Toronto contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>But their expedition was cut short because of heavy rainfall and other conditions they did not expect until mid-July: Temperatures reached 40 degrees, breaking the ice, and strong currents flowed south, making it difficult to walk, paddle, or ski.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>In 2003, it was twice that _ 13 kilometers (8.1 miles) per year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Working with Greenpeace, a nonprofit organization focused on solving environmental problems, Dupre and explorer Eric Larsen, 34, also of Grand Marais, left Siberia for the North Pole on May 12 with two canoe-sleds.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>In 2002-2003, a 10-kilometer (six-mile) stretch of the Sermeq Kujalleq glacier broke off and drifted silently out of the fjord near Ilulissat, Greenland's third largest town, 250 kilometers (155 miles) north of the Arctic Circle.</line><line>Indigenous people who for centuries have adapted their lives to the cold, fear that the changes, however small and gradual, could have a profound impact.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>The team, which finally had to be airlifted out, plans to try again next spring.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>For example, the white sea ice reflects solar radiation back into space, but as the ice melts the dark water will absorb some of the light, warming and melting more ice.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="7" sums="12,21,22,38,42,5,8"><scu uid="136" label="Less ice reflects less sunlight, warming the planet" weight="1"/><scu uid="137" label="warming planet leads to more ice melt" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>When NASA started taking satellite images of the Arctic region in the late 1970s and computer technology improved, scientists noted alarming patterns and theorized they were caused by the emission of so-called greenhouse gases, emitted by industries and internal combustion engines, that create a heat-trapping layer in the atmosphere.</line><line>Many scientists say that position undermines the whole planet and they point to Greenland as the leading edge of what the globe could suffer.</line><line>There is not even unanimity on how much of the problem is a result of human activity, notably the burning of fossil fuels, and how much of it can be attributed to natural processes.</line><line>Polar bears and other animals that depend on sea ice to breed and forage are at risk, scientists say.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>&quot;It is eating up the land,&quot; said Innokenty Koryakin, a member of the Evenk tribe and the captain of a fishing boat.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>And in a span of about 1,000 years, he added, the Greenland ice sheet may disappear, raising Earth's sea level by about six meters (20 feet).</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>But the 140 nations that have signed the pact don't include the United States, which produces one-quarter of the gases.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Meanwhile, one of the fastest melting glaciers in North America has reached the halfway point of disintegration and will continue retreat for another two decades.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Dupre plans to leave in April 2006 for his next Arctic expedition, three weeks earlier than he left this year, and with a little more insight about the effects of global warming.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>Coastal erosion is a problem in Alaska as well, forcing the United States to prepare to relocate several Inuit villages at a projected cost of $100 million or more for each one.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Two of Greenland's largest glaciers are retreating at an alarming pace, most likely because of climate warming, scientists said Wednesday.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="5" sums="11,14,41,44,57"><scu uid="123" label="Glacier Sermeg melted faster" weight="1"/><scu uid="124" label="Glacier Sermilik melted faster" weight="1"/><scu uid="125" label="Glacier Kangerdlugssuag melted faster" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>Climate change has been a hotly discussed issue for decades, but efforts to fight it have moved slowly.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>&quot;We could be underestimating the rate of global temperature increase.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>The rate of ice melting in the Arctic is increasing and a panel of researchers says it sees no natural process that is likely to change that trend.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="10" sums="14,20,22,25,29,43,44,49,5,55"><scu uid="116" label="Arctic sea ice melting faster" weight="2"/><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>Equally, the Inuit need to be out there on the ice catching seals and are less and less able to do that because the ice is more unstable, thinner,&quot; he said.</line><line>Arctic sea ice has decreased by approximately 8 percent, or nearly 1 million square kilometers (386,1000 square miles) over the past 30 years.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>For example, deeper permafrost, largely untouched by recent warming at the surface, would have an influence.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>New species (of plants) come in and suffocate other plants that are the main food for the reindeer,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>But the oscillation has weakened in recent years, and yet the melting continued and even accelerated.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Melting of Greenland ice and calving of icebergs from glaciers is responsible for about 7 percent of the annual rise in global sea level.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="16,37,6"><scu uid="138" label="warming planet and ice melts raises sea level" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>The latest observations through September show that melting in 2005 began a record 17 days earlier than usual.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>Melting of land-based glaciers could take much longer but could raise the sea levels, potentially affecting coastal regions worldwide.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="51"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>They also speculate that this year's unprecedented season of Atlantic storms, spearheaded by Hurricane Katrina which devastated New Orleans, was caused by global warming.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>And as technology improves, oil prices rise and the seasonal ice cap retreats, oil shipments from countries like Norway and Russia are soaring.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>In addition to sea and land ice melting, Overpeck said that the frozen soil layer called permafrost will melt and eventually disappear in some areas.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>The Sermilik glacier in southern Greenland has retreated 11 kilometers (6.84 miles), and the Sermeq Kujalleq glacier near Ilulissat also is moving at a faster pace, said Henrik Hoejmark Thomsen of the geological survey.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="123" label="Glacier Sermeg melted faster" weight="1"/><scu uid="124" label="Glacier Sermilik melted faster" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>&quot;It's become clear that the West Antarctic Ice Sheet, much of which sits on land that's actually below sea level, is one of the most vulnerable in the world to these types of rapid breakdowns,&quot; Clark said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Rich countries, which are most to blame for the problem, will have to make big strides in fuel efficiency and switch to cleaner energy sources.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>&quot;What really makes the Arctic different from the rest of the non-polar world is the permanent ice in the ground, in the ocean, and on land,&quot; said Jonathan T. Overpeck of the University of Arizona and chairman of the National Science Foundation's Arctic System Science Committee that issued the report.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>The computer climate model didn't consider some natural factors that tend to keep the permafrost cold, Romanovsky said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>That session was held in the town of Ilulissat, near the edge of the Sermeq Kujalleq glacier that has retreated nearly seven miles since 1960 and has become a symbol of fears that the planet is approaching a dangerous warming.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Martin made a veiled attack on this position by warning that no-one was immune from climate change.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>Watching the gargantuan chunks of ice break off the Sermeq Kujalleq glacier and thunder into an Arctic fjord is a spectacular sight.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="51,55,57"><scu uid="123" label="Glacier Sermeg melted faster" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>But already, the Kyoto protocol &quot;is not enough&quot;, Tuomioja charged.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>The panel's findings were published in Tuesday's issue of Eos, the weekly newspaper of the American Geophysical Union.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;We can only do that for a month or two now.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>It turned out the location was right, he said, but the glaciers had receded - a mile inland.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>The frequency and size of the crumbling blocks are a powerful reminder that the ice sheet covering the world's largest island is thinning, which scientists say is one of the most glaring examples of global warming.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="33,43"><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>&quot;If that much near-surface permafrost thaws, it could release considerable amounts of greenhouse gases into the atmosphere, and that could amplify global warming,&quot; said lead author David Lawrence, with the National Center for Atmospheric Research.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>US and European scientists fear the collapse of ice shelves in Greenland and Antarctica will raise ocean levels faster than estimated, said a report published Friday in the journal Science.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="11,19,33,41,48,49"><scu uid="131" label="Melting Greenland and Antarctic Ice Shelf double sea level" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>Since satellite observations began in earnest, researchers said Arctic ice has been retreating at a rate of more than 8 percent per decade.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="36"><scu uid="116" label="Arctic sea ice melting faster" weight="2"/><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>In Sisimiut, Greenland's second-largest town, lakes have doubled in size in the last decade.</line><line>&quot;Greenland is the canary in a mine shaft alerting us,&quot; said Corell, the American meteorologist.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>One of the Greenland glaciers, Kangerdlugssuaq, is currently moving at about nine miles (15 kilometers) a year compared to three miles (5 kilometers) a year in 2001, said Gordon Hamilton of the University of Maine's Climate Change Institute.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>The Colorado institute led the study that also involved two NASA laboratories, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the University of Washington.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>He added: &quot;Within short decades, the Northwest passage, the famously unnavigable thoroughfare of history, may be passable -- a striking and unsettling example of our delicate balance succumbing to untenable strain.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;What exactly happened, we don't know but it appears to be the effect of climate change,&quot; said Hoejmark Thomsen.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Environment ministers from around the world heard a grim warning about the threat to the Arctic Wednesday as they began three days of talks to climax a key conference on climate change here.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="23,25"><scu uid="84" label="International meetings address climate change" weight="3"/><scu uid="86" label="international meetings address global warming" weight="3"/><scu uid="69" label="23 countries met" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>&quot;The melting and retreat trends are accelerating,&quot; Ted Scambos, of the University of Colorado at Boulder's National Snow and Ice Data Center, said in a statement released by the university.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>&quot;Winters are growing milder, summers hotter and more severe, there is plant life where before there was none; there is water before there was ice.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>New satellite observations show that sea ice in the Arctic is melting faster while air temperatures in the region are rising sharply, scientists say.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="16" sums="10,11,12,13,14,20,23,25,29,36,43,44,49,5,51,55"><scu uid="116" label="Arctic sea ice melting faster" weight="2"/><scu uid="117" label="New satellite photos show Arctic ice melting faster" weight="1"/><scu uid="118" label="New satellite photos show that Arctic air temperatures rising" weight="1"/><scu uid="119" label="Arctic sea ice area reduced" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Understanding what happens during Alaskan glacier retreat could help explain the phenomenon in Greenland, said Tad Pfeffer, associate director of the University of Colorado's Institute of Arctic and Alpine.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>&quot;Something has fundamentally changed here, and the best answer is warming,&quot; said Mark Serreze, another researcher at the snow and ice data center.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Tackling the pollution is a big headache because of the economic cost.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;We can see a trend that the fall is getting longer and wetter,&quot; said Lars-Anders Baer, a political leader for Sweden's indigenous Sami, a once-nomadic people with a long tradition of reindeer herding.</line><line>Research has also shown that populations of turbot, Atlantic cod and snow crab are no longer found in some parts of the Bering Sea, an important fishing zone between Alaska and Russia, and that flooding along the Lena River, one of Siberia's biggest, has increased with warming temperatures.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Dupre is scheduled to speak about his adventures at Cape Cod Community College in Barnstable Sept. 6 at 6:30 p.m. and to endorse the proposed Cape Cod wind farm, a project to install 130 energy-efficient wind turbines in Nantucket Sound.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>After studying how various parts of the climate system interact, the researchers said there are two major feedback systems influencing the region _ ocean circulation in the North Atlantic and the amount of precipitation and evaporation that takes place.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>And explorer Lonnie Dupre has harrowing firsthand stories to prove it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Global warming is frequently blamed for retreating glaciers around the world.</line><line>The glacier, which moves about 80 feet (24 meters) a day, currently releases about 2 cubic miles (8.3 cubic kilometers) of ice every year into the Prince William Sound on the south coast of Alaska.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>&quot;The one common thread,&quot; Scambos said, &quot;is that Arctic temperatures over the ice, ocean and surrounding land have increased in recent decades.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>&quot;We see all of that ice melting already, and we envision that it will melt back much more dramatically in the future, as we move towards this more permanent ice-free state,&quot; Overpeck said in a statement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>Now the melting trend has spread throughout the Arctic, according to a national collaboration of scientists.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="5,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>But researchers at the annual meeting of the American Geophysical Union also presented studies of the retreat of Alaska's Columbia Glacier that suggest more complexity in the processes of glacial melt.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051019.0285"><line>The discovery of vast petroleum fields in the Barents and Kara Seas has raised fears of catastrophic accidents in the fisheries of Scandinavia.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>Instead, scientists think the retreat is triggered by a slow warming trend that began five centuries ago.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Developing countries, meanwhile, will have to avoid becoming dependent on fossil fuels, which have a big cost advantage over fledging alternative technologies.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051110.0526"><line>Sweden's trade and industry minister, Thomas Oestros, called on the other delegates to follow the lead of his country, which is hoping to become independent of fossil fuels by 2020, by developing the use of biofuels.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>&quot;The time is past to seek comfort in denial.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>&quot;The real problem would occur if these smaller glacial breakups trigger larger ones, and rising sea levels by themselves might cause a feedback mechanism which would further speed up the process,&quot; the scientist added.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>The thinning of the sea ice presents a danger to both humans and polar bears, said Peter Ewins, director of Arctic conservations for the World Wildlife Fund Canada.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>Current projections in climate models suggest that global warming during the next century or two will cause thermal expansion of water and some melting of glacial ice chiefly in Greenland.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="21,40"><scu uid="137" label="warming planet leads to more ice melt" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>&quot;Maybe it will be difficult for him to find the seals,&quot; Utuaq said, resting on a bench in the east coast town of Kulusuk.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>The idea for the expedition came in 2001 during a 6,500-mile trip around Greenland.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Emissions of this carbon pollution have surged in the past century thanks to unbridled use of oil, gas and coal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>Current projections for rises in sea levels do not take into account the new hypothesis, said Peter Clark, professor of geosciences at Oregon State University.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Until then, Dupre plans to tour the United States to share details of his voyage, stress the threat of global warming, and show support for nature as a primary energy source.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>But let's hold our horses because it's not everywhere that the ice is melting.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="25"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051208.0069"><line>&quot;It's quite a staggering rate of increase,&quot; Hamilton said during the AGU meeting.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050823.0999"><line>And changes to the permafrost could undermine buildings, drain water into bogs and release additional carbon into the atmosphere.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>The breakdown of glaciers currently being studied, said Clark, could double the sea level rise to a full meter.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050902.0348"><line>The meeting ended with statements of concern, sincere calls for measure to address the problem _ and no action.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>Scientists say there is mounting evidence that the first effects of climate change are already kicking in, with the melting of Alpine and Himalayan glaciers and erosion of Arctic and Antarctic icesheets.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="13,14,29,38,44,55,8"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051021.0151"><line>&quot;We may be more vulnerable to sea level rise than we thought and it may be more rapid than we have anticipated,&quot; Clark said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051207.0429"><line>The conference gathers ministers or their stand-ins from 189 countries and entities under the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC), the fruit of the 1992 Rio Summit.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>A permafrost researcher at the University of Alaska Fairbanks, however, disagrees that the thaw could be so large.</line><line>Using supercomputers in the United States and Japan, the study calculated how frozen soil would interact with air temperatures, snow, sea ice changes and other processes.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050929.0103"><line>During the 1990s, a cyclical atmospheric circulation pattern called the Arctic Oscillation was believed to have been pushing sea ice out of the region and into adjacent waters.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050830.0051"><line>Call 800-219-9260 or check www.projectthinice.org for more information, and to confirm dates and times.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0273"><line>If air temperatures increase 2 to 4 degrees over the next century, permafrost would begin thawing south of the Brooks Range and start degrading in some places on Alaska's Arctic slope, he said.</line></document></collection>